{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_01NcUVXyqMj5ftExCksVYVHL","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze the source file and convert it to a knowledge file JSON.\n\n**Step 1: Title**\nThe first heading with `=====` underline is \"ユーザ情報登録サービスの仕様\"\n\n**Step 1.5: Check for no-knowledge-content**\nThe source has substantial Layer A and B content - specifications, tables, etc. So `no_knowledge_content: false`.\n\n**Step 2: Build section list**\nRST h2 headings (underlined with `-----` but actually with `====`... let me re-read.\n\nIn RST:\n- h1: underlined with `=====` (the document title)\n\n\n- h2: underlined with `=` when used for sections\n\nLooking at the source more carefully, I can see the heading hierarchy: the main title is overlined and underlined with `=`, then sections like \"機能概要\", \"要求電文仕様\", and \"応答電文仕様\" are underlined with `=` as well, making them h2 level headings.\n\nNow I'm noticing that in RST, the heading level is determined by the order characters first appear in the document, not by specific character assignments. So the `=` character establishes the top level (h1 for the title), and subsequent underlines with `=` for sections would actually be h2 based on the hierarchy established. Looking at the heading structure, I can see all the section headings use `====` underlines, which makes them h2 level headings. There are no `-----` underlines anywhere in the document, so there's no split-level h2 to worry about. The sections are: 機能概要, 要求電文仕様, 応答電文仕様, ステータスコード/障害コード仕様, and エンティティ情報. Since there are no h3 headings with `~~~~~` underlines either, everything stays at h2. Now I'm extracting the content from each section, starting with 機能概要. ユーザ情報テンポラリテーブルへのレコード登録フローを整理している。常駐バッチが一定間隔で監視し、未処理データを検出したときにユーザ情報を登録する仕組みになっている。ここからは要求電文仕様、応答電文仕様、ステータスコード、エンティティ情報といった各レイヤーの仕様を確認していく必要がある。 The service receives user registration messages from external systems, registers the